  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These obligations include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting cash transactions above certain thresholds\n- Alerting financial regulators about potential money laundering\n\n3. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Identifying and verifying customer identities\n- Understanding the nature of customers' business activities\n- Assessing potential money laundering risks\n\n4. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Implementing internal policies and procedures\n- Training employees on money laundering detection\n- Establishing internal monitoring systems\n\n5. Legal Penalties\n- Potential significant financial fines\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Loss of banking licenses\n- Potential personal liability for executives\n\nThese obligations are primarily governed by laws like the Bank Secrecy Act and international regulations designed to prevent financial crimes.",
